In 1599, the Archbishop of St. Andrews had lamented the frequent devastations by war of the Monastery of North Berwick and its lands3⁴and the burning of its Church by the invading enemy.2 Whether the Abbey Church was rebuilt afterwards is now unknown; no vestige of it remains. The ruins now known as the Abbey of North Berwick still show enough to leave no doubt that they are of later structure, apparently about the time of the Reformation, when the Humes, Lords of North Berwick, may have built a dwelling on the site of the old Nunnery. There is no mark of any ecclesiastical building in the existing ruins.
